{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17418283","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17418283"},"attributes":{"position":1,"marks":1,"answeredAt":null,"options":[],"response":null,"finalizedAt":null},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261498"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261498"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2439"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505419","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505419"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:30:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:30:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2439"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261498","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261498"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T10:29:54+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T10:32:06+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":2,"questionsAnswered":1,"marksTotal":1,"marksAttainable":1,"marksAttempted":1,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T10:30:03+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0,"questionsCorrect":0,"marksCorrect":0},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"2439","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2439"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.03,0.92,0.03,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2439"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47310"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2439","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2439"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2439"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32029"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"2173"},{"type":"tags","id":"2371"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11059"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1923"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1929"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7239"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10397"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10440"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12167"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30490"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42491"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43152"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47310","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/47310"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 48-year-old woman presents to her general practitioner due to changes in her menstrual cycle over the past six months. She reports having irregular and shorter periods which lasted less than two days and her periods have been coming 28\u201335 days as opposed to her usual 25-day cycle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOver the past few months, she complains of disturbed sleep due to night sweats and hot flushes. She also feels increasingly tired, has gained six kg over the past four months and has felt \u0027extra heart beats\u0027 on occasion. She is sexually active with her husband of 20 years and does not use contraception. There is no history of post-coital bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EExamination shows heart rate of 98 beats/min, blood pressure 118/76 mmHg. Initial investigations show a thyroid-stimulating hormone of 4.9 mIU/L (0.5\u20135.0) and free T4 of 17 pmol/L (10\u201320), normal complete blood examination, normal iron studies. Serum beta human chorionic gonadotropin is negative. Her cervical screening two years ago was normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hyperprolactinemia","TSH-mediated hyperthyroidism","Perimenopause","Primary ovarian insufficiency","Pheochromocytoma"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is a case of \u003Cstrong\u003Eperimenopause\u003C/strong\u003E. Perimenopause often presents with symptoms related to oestrogen withdrawal including menstrual cycle irregularities, mood changes, hot flushes, weight gain and palpitations. Perimenopause commonly starts at around 45-55 years of age. Due to the fluctuations of oestrogen hormone, oestrogen level is not a good indicator of perimenopause and given the patient is still having periods a follicular stimulating hormone will not change management. Diagnosis of perimenopause should be made clinically, and investigations should only be done to exclude other differentials - such as hyperthyroidism and assess cardiovascular risk profile if menopausal hormone replacement treatment is considered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyperprolactinemia\u003C/strong\u003E can cause menstrual cycle dysfunction. Common causes of hyperprolactinemia include pregnancy, breastfeeding, stress, prolactinomas and various drugs (eg. antipsychotics). However, hyperprolactinemia classically presents with other clinical features including galactorrhea. Additionally, hyperprolactinemia is not associated with night sweats and hot flushes. As such, on the balance of probability perimenopause is more likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003EHyperthyroidism\u003C/strong\u003E can mimic symptoms of perimenopause and is often misdiagnosed. The patient has a normal thyroid-stimulating hormone level, excluding current, symptomatic hyperthyroidism. It is important to rule out thyroid dysfunction in a patient presenting with these symptoms, so serum thyroid stimulating hormone (TSH) is an appropriate investigation. \u003Cstrong\u003ETSH-mediated hyperthyroidism\u003C/strong\u003E (e.g. hyperthyroidism due to a TSH-secreting pituitary adenomas) classically presents with a normal or elevated TSH, and an elevated free T3/T4. TSH-mediated hyperthyroidism is very rare and the patient has no other clinical features of the condition (eg. diffuse goitre, visual field deficits, or headache).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimary ovarian insufficiency\u003C/strong\u003E also known as premature ovarian insufficiency is a condition in which women under the age of 40 have decline in ovarian function and reduction in production of oestrogen. It presents with symptoms of perimenopause, however the patient\u0027s age excludes this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Epheochromocytoma\u003C/strong\u003E classically presents with episodic headache, hypertension, sweating, and tachycardia. It is an important diagnosis to consider in the context of night sweats or generalised hyperhidrosis, and menstrual dysfunction is an uncommon but potential complication of pheochromocytoma. That said, this presentation is very rare so the diagnosis is unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Perimenopause can mimic the symptoms of other medical conditions including hyperthyroidism, and a thorough history is required.","A diagnosis of perimenopause is made based on clinical assessment."],"references":["Trivalle C, Doucet J, Chassagne P, et al. Differences in the signs and symptoms of hyperthyroidism in older and younger patients. J Am Geriatr Soc 1996; 44:50.","Krassas GE, Pontikides N, Kaltsas T, et al. Menstrual disturbances in thyrotoxicosis. Clin Endocrinol (Oxf) 1994; 40:641.","Woods NF, Mitchell ES. Symptoms during the perimenopause: prevalence, severity, trajectory, and significance in women\u0027s lives. Am J Med 2005; 118 Suppl 12B:14.","Wakil A, Atkin S. Secondary amenorrhoea due to pheochromocytoma: a case report. Cases J. 2008 Jul 11;1(1):30."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32029"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2439"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"32029","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/32029"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-06-20T07:33:11+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-10T18:41:34+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2439"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"47310"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHe